dog_history: Available to care for dogs from teacup size to horse! rrI grew up in a household that was pretty unique - my Mom was active with PAWS and we always had a foster dog, cat or other animal recovering from illness in our home. I also grew up with several pets of my own: Heidi the deaf kitty, Barney the huge part wolf part German Shepard, Perle (short for Crown Crest Persian Perle) a show Saluki who everyone thought was malnourished based on her extremely lean physique and many toads and frogs!rrI have cared for dogs with cancer and other illnesses and nursed our last dog Chrissy, back to health, after a horrible reaction to a vaccination, so we know what to do in a palliative setting or in an emergency.rrMy husband is a big strong guy at 6" and 280lbs, so big dogs are zero problem, and I can handle them well myself.  I also have an 8 year old little boy who would love to help me look after a dog :-)

I quickly learned that having a puppy requires a lifetime of patience and that the unconditional love that they give in return is more than worth it. As she grew into a very sweet and loyal pup to myself and most humans, I also noticed that she grew increasingly unpleasant with other dogs. dog_history: I was born a dog lover, well any animal lover. I had a golden retriever when I was 3 and he was my first dog. We use to play around together before he got a tumor and past away. For the past 14 years, I've had my Chihuahua/Wiener dog mix, her name is Trixie and she is my dog. I taught her how to walk and use to feed her through a baby doll bottle, we got her when she was only a month old. The mother didn't have enough milk to feed her and she would've died. She's very lovable and caring, although Trixie is fully blind from cataracts. I have taken care of my uncles cat, spunky when he was alive for 2 years until he passed. Not only that I have saved dogs from being chained up and abused, I'm an avid dog sponsor since they can't talk.

I have been a dog lover since before I can remember. At 3 years old I trained my step dad's border collie to "sit" in response to a hand signal (this dog only responded to me, a 3 year old)!. By the age of 10 I was both babysitting AND dog-sitting for other people's dogs. By 19 years of age I had spent 3 years as an assistant to a service dog trainer. I, for about a year, worked as an assistant to a veterinary technician. I can clip a dog's nails, brush their teeth, groom them, and more IN ADDITION to providing basic care like walks, exercise, companionship! Lastly, as an assistant to a service-dog trainer I can help with a dog's basic commands: sit, stay, come, down, wait, leave-it, leash manners and more!I think brushing a dog's teeth or clipping their nails is proof enough that I LOVE them (I mean this jokingly; I just realize not many people like taking care of these tasks). Frankly, I think there has never been a time when I wasn't taking care of and loving dogs in some capacity.

Beginning with my first dog Bailey, a stray German short-haired pointer that my family adopted after unsuccessfully searching for his owners. I used to love throwing the tennis ball for him and having him point his foot before each throw.rSince Bailey I have had a German Shepard named Sasha, whom my father trained on his DIY agility course he built for her in the backyard. Sadly she was hit by a semi-truck along with Bailey when she was only 6 years old.rAfter Sasha I got to pick out my own first puppy, Roxy, a Basset Hound. She was my favorite pet, even though the responsibilities of caring for her seemed to grow each year. She would always make me smile no matter what she was doing, every position she just looked hilarious. rDuring high school I took my first job working with animals at the local animal shelter in San Diego where I taught children about the proper care of all pets, including dogs and cats. We taught kids from 4-13 about how to meet a dog for

We were the family who took in all the strays and found them homes.  Our first family dog came in with the paperboy during a blizzard. The neighborhood dogs always came to our house when they got away, because they knew they would be treated like royalty!    We dog-sat often, and I have taken care of dogs independently since college.  As a kid, I was obsessed with dogs and dog breeds, and this has been passed on to my daughter.
